      <hedline>
        <hl1>Turks and Armenians</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rodney B Wagner letter on Sept 27 article oppose House resolution labeling as genocide 1915 killings of Armenians in Turkey</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I am disappointed by the support for a House resolution labeling as genocide the 1915 killings of Armenians in Turkey (World Briefing item, Sept. 27). The events were difficult to judge even then.</p>
        <p>It was a painful time in a country at war and beset by nationalist separatism. Many thousands died in Anatolia, the majority being Muslim Turks. The supposed genocide was investigated in 1919 by the British authorities occupying Istanbul, and charges against the accused were dropped.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I am disappointed by the support for a House resolution labeling as genocide the 1915 killings of Armenians in Turkey (World Briefing item, Sept. 27). The events were difficult to judge even then.</p>
        <p>It was a painful time in a country at war and beset by nationalist separatism. Many thousands died in Anatolia, the majority being Muslim Turks. The supposed genocide was investigated in 1919 by the British authorities occupying Istanbul, and charges against the accused were dropped.</p>
        <p>Approving this resolution would delay the rapprochement between Turkey and Armenia. It would also drive a wedge between the United States and its strategic partner, Turkey, at a time when regional cooperation is so valuable.</p>
        <p>RODNEY B. WAGNER  Istanbul, Sept. 28, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is chairman of the board of trustees, Robert College of Istanbul.</p>
      </block>
